#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:1
msgid "Querying and resetting arrays to process"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:3
msgid ""
"To support filters that allow users to configure an arbitrary number of "
"arrays to process, `vtkAlgorithm` now provides two new methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:6
msgid ""
"`GetNumberOfInputArraySpecifications()` returns the number of arrays the "
"algorithm is currently configured to process; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:8
msgid ""
"`ResetInputArraySpecifications()` removes all array specifications so the "
"filter behaves as if `SetInputArrayToProcess()` has never been called. This "
"also marks the filter as modified if it had an effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:12
msgid "Specify array components to process"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:14
msgid ""
"Your algorithm or pipeline can now specify not just an array to process, but "
"also a component of that array, using new overloaded signatures of the "
"`vtkAlgorithm::SetInputArrayToProcess()` method. This also includes support "
"for L₁, L₂, or L∞ norms of tuples rather than choosing a single tuple to be "
"processed. The different norms are computed like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:20
msgid ""
"The L₁ norm is the sum of the absolute values of each component in a tuple. "
"For a tuple (3, -4, 12), the L₁ norm is |3| + |-4| + |12| = 19."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:22
msgid ""
"The L₂ norm is the square root of the sum of the squares of each component "
"in the input tuple. For a tuple (3, -4, 12), the L₂ norm is sqrt(9 + 16 + "
"144) = 13."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:25
msgid ""
"The L∞ norm is the maximum of the absolute value of each component. For a "
"tuple (3, 4, -12), the L∞ norm is max(|3|,|4|,|-12|) = 12."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:28
msgid ""
"Similarly, algorithms can now ask their parent `vtkAlgorithm` class to pass "
"them a single-component array holding the component/norm requested above "
"rather than extracting the component of the array specified by the pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:32
msgid "Asking a filter to process input components"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:34
msgid ""
"Let's consider 3 examples to illustrate what's changed and what hasn't. "
"We'll assume your data has a vector-valued cell-data array named `velocity` "
"with 3 components and you want to pass it to a `filter` that uses a single "
"component of the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:38
msgid ""
"Call `filter->SetInputArrayToProcess(0, 0, 0, vtkDataObject::"
"FIELD_ASSOCIATION_CELL, \"velocity\");` to have `filter` treat each tuple as "
"it has in the past (where each tuple has 3 components). This uses pre-"
"existing methods and works just as it has in the past."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:41
msgid ""
"Call `filter->SetInputArrayToProcess(0, 0, 0, vtkDataObject::"
"FIELD_ASSOCIATION_CELL, \"velocity\", 1);` to have `filter` use only the _y_ "
"component of the velocity vector."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:43
msgid ""
"Call `filter->SetInputArrayToProcess(0, 0, 0, vtkDataObject::"
"FIELD_ASSOCIATION_CELL, \"velocity\", vtkArrayComponents::L2Norm);` to have "
"`filter` process the L₂-norm of the each velocity tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:46
msgid ""
"As you can see, `SetInputArrayToProcess` now takes an optional value at the "
"end of its arguments to indicate either a non-negative component number or a "
"special enumerant from the `vtkArrayComponents` enum to indicate a norm "
"should be computed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:50
msgid "Processing array components inside your algorithm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:52
msgid ""
"There is also a new method of `vtkAlgorithm` called "
"`GetInputArrayComponent()` that you can use to determine whether the "
"pipeline is requesting a specific component or not. If the array is intended "
"to be taken as-is (i.e., use all components of the tuple), then the value "
"returned will be `vtkArrayComponents::AllComponents`. Otherwise, the "
"returned integer will be either non-negative (indicating a specific "
"component) or a value from the `vtkArrayComponents` enum indicating a norm "
"should be computed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:59
msgid ""
"To make using specific components of arrays easier, `vtkAlgorithm` now also "
"provides methods named `vtkAlgorithm::GetInputArray()` that will *either* "
"return the original array or – if a component/norm is requested – create a "
"new array instance that holds the configured component (or computed norm). "
"It calls the new `vtk::ComponentOrNormAsArray()` in its implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:64
msgid ""
"String- and variant-arrays support production of new single-component arrays "
"of the same type as the input for components (but obviously do not support "
"computing norms). To implement this behavior, the `CopyComponent()` method "
"of `vtkDataArray` has been moved to `vtkAbstractArray` and its signature "
"modified to accept abstract arrays as inputs. The original signature on "
"`vtkDataArray` has been kept as an overload to avoid the overhead of safe-"
"downcasting to a data-array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:71
msgid ""
"Because a smart-pointer to the array is returned, you can use it inside "
"`RequestData()` without worrying about deleting it before returning. You can "
"also override the requested component it fetches if your algorithm needs "
"access to other tuple data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:75
msgid ""
"There is also a templated method `GetInputArrayAs<ArrayType>()` that will "
"return a smart-pointer of the templated parameter (usually `vtkDataArray`) "
"so you can call methods as needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:78
msgid "To match the 3 examples above, you can simply call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:80
msgid ""
"  vtkDataObject* input;\n"
"  int association;\n"
"  vtkSmartPointer<vtkDataArray> arrayToProcess = filter->GetInputArray(0, "
"input, association);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:86
msgid ""
"and you'll be passed – depending on which of the 3 respective cases above "
"you consider:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:88
msgid ""
"the original array with 3 components (_x_, _y_, _z_) as the user indicated "
"`velocity` should be processed as a vector."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:90
msgid ""
"a new array of the same type with 1 component but the same number of tuples "
"as the `velocity` array; each tuple will hold only the _y_ component of "
"`velocity`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:92
msgid ""
"a new double-valued array with 1 component but the same number of tuples as "
"the `velocity` array; each tuple will hold the L₂ norm (= sqrt(_x² + y² + "
"z²_)) of each tuple in `velocity`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:95
msgid ""
"When L₁ or L₂ norms are requested, the array returned to you will have "
"`double`-precision values. All other norm- and component-selections will "
"return arrays whose type matches the input array type. Thus, if `velocity` "
"was a `vtkCharArray` and an L∞ norm was requested, you will be passed a "
"`char`-valued array back. This was done since the L₁ and L₂ norms may run "
"into overflow and/or precision issues if the storage type of component "
"values is used to hold norm values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:102
msgid ""
"Futhermore, if your algorithm requires a single-component array, you can "
"pass an additional `requestedComponent` parameter to `GetInputArray()` "
"specifying a default component (usually 0) or norm so that if the user "
"configures a multi-component array you will always extract a meaningful "
"default component. For example, consider this snippet:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:107
msgid ""
"  vtkAlgorithm* filter;\n"
"  int compOrNorm;\n"
"  filter->SetInputArrayToProcess(\n"
"    0, 0, 0, vtkDataObject::FIELD_ASSOCIATION_POINTS, \"a1\", compOrNorm);\n"
"  vtkSmartPointer<vtkDataArray> arrayToProcess =\n"
"    filter->GetInputArray(0, input, association, vtkArrayComponents::"
"L2Norm);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:116
msgid "If `compOrNorm` is"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:118
msgid ""
"a valid component index or one of the norm enumerants of "
"`vtkArrayComponents`, then `arrayToProcess` will be the specified component "
"or norm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:120
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayComponents::AllComponents`, then `arrayToProcess` will be a single-"
"component array that evaluates to the L₂-norm of each tuple of \"a1\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:123
msgid ""
"This way, `arrayToProcess` will never be a multi-component array, regardless "
"of whether the \"a1\" point-data array on the input dataset is."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:126
msgid "Modified vtkDataArray::CopyComponents signature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:128
msgid ""
"As mentioned above, the `CopyComponent()` method of `vtkDataArray` has been "
"moved to `vtkAbstractArray` and its signature modified to accept abstract "
"arrays as inputs. This means you may copy components of variant- and string-"
"valued arrays (into other variant- and string-arrays; no type conversion is "
"attempted)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.6/algorithm-array-components.md:133
msgid ""
"Also, it returns a boolean indicating whether component-copying was "
"successful (true) or not (false). The method will still print error messages "
"in the case of failure. The original signature on `vtkDataArray` has been "
"kept as an overload to avoid the overhead of safe-downcasting to a data-"
"array."
msgstr ""
